We notice a recent work (Xu et al., 2022) proposed a random
backdoor attack on FedGL inspired by (Zhang et al., 2021a; Xie et al., 2019). Specifically, it
uses a subgraph as a trigger, and
each malicious client randomly generates the trigger shape and randomly picks nodes from local graphs as the location to inject the trigger.
However, our results show this attack
attains unsatisfactory backdoor performance (see Table 1).

Table 1 shows the comparison results of the attacks in the default setting (more comprehensive comparison and more results are shown in Table 9-Table 14
in Appendix D.1).
We have the below key observations:

Global trigger vs. local triggers:
From Table 1, we know the MA performance is marginally affected by the backdoor attacks with respect to different trigger sizes.
Recall that, during testing, we use the combined local triggers to form a global trigger (a complete subgraph), which is injected into all testing graphs. In this experiment, we
also explore the BA performance of our Opt-GDBA where each client uses the local triggers generated by its own trigger generator.
Specifically, we use ρ=20%𝜌percent20\rho=20\% and the total number of malicious clients is 20%∗50%∗40=4percent20percent5040420\%*50\%*40=4.
Figure 6 compares the BA produced by the global trigger vs. local triggers per malicious client with Definable-Trigger Opt-GDBA with nt​r​i=4subscript𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑖4n_{tri}=4.
For instance, “Local triggers 1” means the local triggers are generated via malicious client 1’s trigger generator on the corresponding testing graphs.

Certified MA vs. ρ𝜌\rho:
In this experiment, we assess the defense performance on Opt-GDBA attacked FedGL models with varying ρ𝜌\rho of malicious clients.
Figure 10 shows the results with T=30𝑇30T=30 and nt​r​i=4subscript𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑖4n_{tri}=4. We observe the certified MA and certified perturbation size are similar with different ρ𝜌\rho’s (except a slight drop when ρ=30%𝜌percent30\rho=30\%).
This is primarily because the Opt-GDBA’s MA and BA are relatively stable across different ρ𝜌\rho, as shown in Table 1.
This ensures the number of correctly predicted subgraphs via our ensemble classifier is also close in different ρ𝜌\rho’s, and so do the certified MA and certified perturbation size.

Our Opt-GDBA uses two schemes to decide the trigger location: Customized-Trigger automatically learns it, while Definable-Trigger predefines it.
Table 2 shows the comparison results.

in most cases.
Note that the MA and BA of the two schemes are close. This hence reflects the Customized-Trigger scheme can further locate the “more important” region in a graph to attach the trigger.

(Persistence) Finetuning the backdoored FedGL model with clean graphs cannot remove the backdoor effect:
A straightforward strategy to mitigate the backdoor effect is to finetune the FedGL model only with clean graphs. To simulate this, we extend the FedGL training with an extra 200 iterations (e.g., from 200 to 400) which only involves training with clean graphs. Table 4 shows the results.
We can see the BA with finetuning is close to that without finetuing in all ρ𝜌\rho and when the trigger node size is not large (i.e., nt​r​i=3,4subscript𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑖34n_{tri}=3,4). This shows the backdoor effect is persistent.

In this experiment, we evaluate the robustness of the backdoored testing graphs generated by our Opt-GDBA under our defense.
Table 6 shows the results of
certified BA.
We observe the certified BA is 0
in all T𝑇T, ρ𝜌\rho, and nt​r​isubscript𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑖n_{tri}.
Recall our graph division strategy ensures the divided subgraphs have non-overlapping edges and node features.
The above results can be attributed to two aspects:
the trigger in the backdoored testing graph is separated into: 1) a few subgraphs that are still classified as the target label, but the other majority subgraphs are mostly classified as a non-target label (actually the true label in most cases);
or 2) a large number of the subgraphs that makes it difficult to form any effective trigger in the subgraphs.
In either case, the number of successful backdoored subgraphs is a minority. Hence, with the majority voting, all the backdoored testing graphs are misclassified as a non-target label.
The results imply the backdoored testing graphs generated by our Opt-GDBA are completely
broken by our graph division + ensemble classifier based defense.
